"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906322","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-05-24","<p>As at 22 May 2018 a total of 2,541 organisations have signed the Armed Forces Covenant. Details of all Armed Forces Covenant signatories and their pledges are available on the gov.uk website at the following link:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/policies/armed-forces-covenant.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-05-24T15:00:18.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906322/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906322/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906322/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-05-17","Armed Forces Covenant","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many businesses have signed up to the Armed Forces Covenant since its commencement.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","145378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906323","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-05-22","<p>The Government will fully fund the removal and replacement of dangerous Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) cladding on buildings owned by councils and housing associations, with costs estimated at £400 million. Some of these buildings will contain leaseholders and shared ownership properties. In the social sector, all of those local authorities and housing associations with whom we are in discussion with have indicated that they are choosing not to pass on the costs of the remediation of cladding systems to individual flat owners within their buildings. The Secretary of State made it clear that he considers this is the right approach.</p><p>In the private sector, building owners are responsible for making buildings safe. We have been clear we think they or the developers of the buildings should pay and not pass costs on to leaseholders, either funding the work themselves or looking at alternative routes such as insurance claims, warranties or action to ensure those responsible for erecting unsafe cladding pay. Leaseholders can challenge the costs in courts if they are unreasonable.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-05-22T15:37:40.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906323/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906323/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906323/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-17","Buildings: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to his Department's press release, Government announces it will fully fund unsafe cladding removal in social housing, published on 16 May 2018, what assessment he has made of the effect on residents in mixed-use developments who are (a) leaseholders or (b) are in shared ownership.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","145263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906324","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-05-23","<p>As at 12 April, our testing programme at Building Research Establishment (BRE) has identified 317 buildings with Aluminium Composite Materials (ACM) cladding in England. Of these, 304 have cladding systems which the expert panel advise are unlikely to meet current building regulations guidance and therefore present fire hazards on buildings over 18 metres. (Of the 304 buildings: 158 are social housing, 14 are public buildings, 101 are private residential and 31 are student residential.) We publish the most recent figures on the Government website every month.</p><p>Every month the Department publishes its latest figures in a data release. The latest can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/building-safety-programme-monthly-data-release-april-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/building-safety-programme-monthly-data-release-april-2018</a></p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-05-23T14:44:04.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906324/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906324/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906324/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-17","Buildings: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, when his Department plans to publish the full list of buildings identified as having cladding which requires removing and replacing.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","145264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906325","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-05-23","<p>In the private sector, building owners are responsible for making buildings safe. We have been clear we think they or the developers of the buildings should pay and not pass costs on to leaseholders, either funding the work themselves or looking at alternative routes such as insurance claims, warranties or action to ensure those responsible for erecting unsafe cladding pay. Leaseholders can challenge the costs in courts if they are unreasonable.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-05-23T11:18:53.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906325/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906325/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906325/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-17","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, with reference to his Department's press release, Government announces it will fully fund unsafe cladding removal in social housing, published on 16 May 2018, what plans his Department has for similar support for leaseholders in private blocks.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","145265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906326","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-22","<p>The Cabinet discussed the Gaza events, on the basis of a briefing by the Foreign Secretary on 15 May.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-05-22T16:11:49.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906326/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906326/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906326/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-17","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with Cabinet colleagues on the recent violence at the Palestinian border.","false","Biography information for Thelma Walker","Colne Valley","Thelma Walker","145397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906327","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-22","<p>At the UN Security Council Meeting in question, the UK Permanent Representative urged Israel to ensure that its security forces did not resort to the use of excessive force, and noted the urgent need to establish why such a volume of live fire continued to be deemed justified.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-05-22T16:07:16.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906327/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906327/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906327/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-17","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the Government condemned the violence used by Israeli forces on protesters at the Gaza-Israel border at the recent UN Security Council meeting.","false","Biography information for Thelma Walker","Colne Valley","Thelma Walker","145398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906328","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-05-25","<p>Arbitration data is published quarterly by the Office of the Pubs Code Adjudicator. The most recent release shows that between 21 July 2016, when the Pubs Code came into force, and 31 March 2018 there were 262 referrals of which 216 had been accepted for arbitration. 109 of the cases accepted for arbitration have concluded.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-05-25T13:48:57.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906328/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906328/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906328/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-17","Pubs Code Adjudicator","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many cases have been submitted to the Office of the Pub Code Adjudicator; and how many such cases have been concluded since its inception.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","145379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906329","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-24","<p>On 1 August 2017, the Government implemented the revised funding system for nursing, midwifery and allied health professional students, meaning that courses in these professions are no longer centrally commissioned.</p><p> </p><p>Further to the announcement of 9 May, the Government is considering the most effective way to implement the ‘golden hello’ incentive scheme for postgraduate nursing students.</p><p> </p><p>The current intention is that these payment incentives will be made available for future postgraduates who completed courses funded by loans in the 2018/19 academic year. The golden hello payments are anticipated to be contingent on these graduates working in specific fields of the health and care sector including mental health, learning disability and community, including district, nursing.</p><p> </p><p>The detail of the scheme is being developed by the Department. Officials will engage with stakeholders as part of finalising proposals; including determining whether it is in the best interests of the National Health Service to split out the numbers eligible for a payment determined by branch of nursing. The conclusions of this will inform assessments of the potential impact of such incentives.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-05-24T15:56:26.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906329/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906329/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906329/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-17","Mental Health: Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many mental health nursing commissions his Department plans to offer in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","145380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906330","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-05-29","<p>We have long been committed to Channel 4 moving out of London, and welcome Channel 4's agreement to move 300 staff out of London, rising over time. There are many creative locations across the UK, including in the North West, which could see a significant positive economic impact from Channel 4 relocating staff. The decision on new out of London locations will be taken by Channel 4, and Channel 4 has said it will take this decision in Q3 2018.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-05-29T08:58:00.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906330/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906330/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906330/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-05-17","Channel 4 Television","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment his Department has made of the potential economic benefits to the North West of relocating Channel 4 to Merseyside.","false","Biography information for Damien Moore","Southport","Damien Moore","145404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906331","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-22","<p>Post-signature contract management is at the core of the Department for Transport’s rail franchising operational management. A dedicated contract and commercial management function is employed to monitor and ensure train operating companies deliver their contractual obligations, in relation to the delivery of services, passenger benefits, and ongoing reporting and management requirements. In addition there is an independent Enforcement Advisory Panel, to which all contraventions of franchise agreements are reported and responded to in a proportionate manner.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-05-22T14:40:47.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906331/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906331/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906331/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-17","Train Operating Companies: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the level of compliance of franchised train operating companies with the terms of their franchise agreements.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","145267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906332","Treasury","false","2018-05-22","<p>According to the Bank of England’s Money and Credit data, the outstanding level of consumer credit, in nominal terms, was £183.9bn in March 2010, compared to £209.4bn in March 2018.</p><p> </p><p>The government established the independent Financial Policy Committee (FPC), giving the FPC a primary objective to identify, monitor and take action to remove or reduce systemic risks with a view to protecting and enhancing financial stability. Following the Bank of England’s 2017 stress test, the FPC said that regulatory capital buffers for individual firms should now be set so that each bank can absorb losses on consumer lending, alongside all the other effects of the stress test on its balance sheet. This will ensure lenders are resilient to any defaults related to consumer credit.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-05-22T15:57:01.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906332/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906332/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906332/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-05-17","Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment his Department has made of trends in the level of consumer credit since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","145268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906333","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-05-22","<p>We do not hold centrally an annual breakdown of spending for victims of domestic violence in the West Midlands since 2010, however, the Government is providing financial support to specialist services for BAME women who are victims of domestic violence in a number of ways through our Violence against Women and Girls (VAWG) Strategy. This includes Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government (MHCLG) funding to local authorities for domestic abuse services and the VAWG Service Transformation Fund</p><p>Since 2014 MHCLG have invested over £33 million in services to support victims of domestic abuse, including support for BAME victims. The MHCLG Priorities for Domestic Abuse Services, which set out what steps local areas should take in their response to domestic abuse, includes the need to consider provision for BAME victims. These priorities encourage the securing of specialist services and using their expertise and knowledge to identify and deal with barriers to service access and deliver the support that BAME victims need when they need it.</p><p>In addition, the VAWG Service Transformation Fund launched in 2017 has provided £17 million to 41 projects and meets the needs of those women and girls experiencing multiple disadvantage (BAME, LGB&amp;T women and girls and disabled and older women). In the West Midlands, we provided £250,000 to Staffordshire PCC for a FGM project to ensure victims and potential victims have timely access to counselling and therapeutic support.</p><p>In 2017, the Government funded the charity Imkaan to build capacity in the BME women’s sector.</p><p>Significant further funding for domestic abuse services, including refuges will be available as early as possible in this financial year. This new fund will be open to all local areas across England to bid for a share.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2018-05-22T15:24:53.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906333/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906333/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906333/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-17","Victim Support Schemes: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what financial support the Government allocated to specialist services for BAME women who are victims of domestic violence in the West Midlands in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","145269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906334","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-23","<p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State has received 10 written representations from the hospice sector; raising concerns about the potential increase in their costs if they choose to increase pay in line with the proposed Agenda for Change pay rates.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","145519","2018-05-23T12:36:11.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906334/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906334/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906334/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-17","Hospices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what representations he has received from the hospice movement on the impact proposed increases in NHS pay; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Derek Thomas","St Ives","Derek Thomas","145389"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906335","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-22","<p>I last raised this range of issues with the Saudi authorities in February. The Prime Minister and the Foreign Secretary did likewise during a visit of the Crown Prince to the UK in March. We also raise our concerns about human rights with the Saudi authorities through our Ambassador and Embassy staff.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-05-22T16:42:59.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906335/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906335/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906335/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-17","Saudi Arabia: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions has he had with his Saudi Arabian counterpart on respect for human rights in that country.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","145270"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906336","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-23","<p>The proposed Agenda for Change pay framework, which includes contract reform and pay awards over three years, is currently out to consultation with the National Health Service trades unions and the outcome will be known in June.</p><p> </p><p>The Chancellor was explicit that additional funding was tied to extensive reforms to the terms and conditions of staff employed on the Agenda for Change contract.</p><p> </p><p>We are considering the impact of the agreement on non-NHS organisations such as hospices that may be affected by the proposed deal however no decisions have been made.</p><p> </p><p>Staff in hospices do a fantastic job in delivering world-class care. The Department remains fully committed to improving palliative and end of life care.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","145391 ; 145520","2018-05-23T10:44:08.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906336/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906336/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906336/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-17","Hospices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether his Department has made an assessment of the effect of the proposed NHS pay increases on sustainability of voluntary sector hospices.","false","Biography information for Derek Thomas","St Ives","Derek Thomas","145390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906337","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-23","<p>The proposed Agenda for Change pay framework, which includes contract reform and pay awards over three years, is currently out to consultation with the National Health Service trades unions and the outcome will be known in June.</p><p> </p><p>The Chancellor was explicit that additional funding was tied to extensive reforms to the terms and conditions of staff employed on the Agenda for Change contract.</p><p> </p><p>We are considering the impact of the agreement on non-NHS organisations such as hospices that may be affected by the proposed deal however no decisions have been made.</p><p> </p><p>Staff in hospices do a fantastic job in delivering world-class care. The Department remains fully committed to improving palliative and end of life care.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","145390 ; 145520","2018-05-23T10:44:08.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906337/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906337/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/906337/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-17","Hospices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether voluntary hospices will be entitled to receive a proportion of the additional Government funding for the proposed NHS pay increases.","false","Biography information for Derek Thomas","St Ives","Derek Thomas","145391"
