"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905482","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-05-21","<p>The Government is undertaking a wide range of ongoing analysis in support of our EU Exit negotiations and preparations. We have been engaging with relevant stakeholders from all sectors of the economy and all regions of the UK as part of this process, and will continue to do so as we move forward.</p><p> </p><p>We have been clear the Government will not provide an ongoing commentary on internal analytical work that is being carried out within government.</p><p> </p><p>As part of our future partnership with the EU, the UK will look to establish an ambitious future agreement on science and innovation that ensures the valuable research links between us continue to grow.</p><p> </p><p>In March 2018, the UK and EU negotiating teams reached an important milestone in the Brexit process by agreeing the terms of a time-limited implementation period. The draft Withdrawal Agreement reflects the text of the December Joint Report, which envisages that UK entities’ right to participate in EU programmes will be unaffected by the UK’s withdrawal from the EU.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the UK Government has committed to underwrite Horizon 2020 funding if necessary. This guarantees funding for UK participants in projects ongoing at the point of exit, as well as any successful bids submitted before the UK leaves the EU.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-05-21T13:54:52.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905482/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905482/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905482/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-16","Science and Technology: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on the science and technology sectors in (a) the West Midlands and (b) Coventry.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","144792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905483","Home Office","false","2018-05-25","<p>Data is available from 30 September 2012. Since that time Members of Parliament have reported immigration abuse 19 times in 2012, 113 in 2013, 101 in 2014, 219 in 2015, 162 in 2016, 73 in 2017 and 36 to date in 2018.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-05-25T09:47:40.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905483/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905483/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905483/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-16","Immigration: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many reports of immigration crime his Department received from hon. Members in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","144781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905484","Home Office","false","2018-05-24","<p>Data is available from 30 September 2012. Since that time records show that the Department for Work and Pensions did not share any intelligence concerning immigration abuse in 2012, they shared it once in 2013, 171 in 2014, 1,377 in 2015, 1,544 in 2016, 1,123 in 2017 and on 262 occasions to date in 2018.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-05-24T16:35:13.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905484/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905484/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905484/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-16","Immigration: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many reports of immigration crime his Department received from the Department for Work and Pensions in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","144782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905485","Home Office","false","2018-05-24","<p>The Home Office recorded receipt of information from Members of Parliament on 73 occasions. Of those 12 were received via the online service, 48 by email, 2 by fax, 9 by letter and 2 by telephone.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-05-24T16:33:40.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905485/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905485/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905485/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-16","Immigration: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many communications his Department received from hon. Members and their offices on immigration enforcement hotlines during 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","144783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905486","Home Office","false","2018-05-24","<p>Data is available from 30 September 2012. Since that time members of the public reported to the Home Office 9,003 times in 2012, 54,809 in 2013, 47,317 in 2014, 50,126 in 2015, 45,539 in 2016, 43,356 in 2017 and 15,999 times to date in 2018.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-05-24T16:31:29.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905486/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905486/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905486/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-16","Immigration: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many reports of immigration crime his Department received from members of the public in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","144784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905487","Home Office","false","2018-05-24","<p>Data is available from 30 September 2012. Since that time records show that Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs did not share intelligence concerning immigration abuse with the Home Office in 2012 or 2013 and did so subsequently on 41 occasions in 2014, 319 in 2015, 259 in 2016, 151 in 2017 and on 62 occasions to date in 2018.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-05-24T16:29:31.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905487/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905487/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905487/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-16","Immigration: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many reports of immigration crime his Department received from HMRC in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","144785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905488","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-05-22","<p>(a-c) The Department does not hold financial outturn data categorised by region or constituency. HMT release their analysis of total public expenditure spend by region in the Country and Regional Analysis. This can be found here: <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/657987/Country_and_Regional_Analysis_November_2017.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/657987/Country_and_Regional_Analysis_November_2017.pdf</a></p><p>(d) The Department does not hold the information requested. Public expenditure on housing will include Housing Benefit, MHCLG expenditure and local authority costs. HMT publish their country and regional analysis which provides the estimate requested for England. <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/country-and-regional-analysis#history" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/country-and-regional-analysis#history</a></p><p> </p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-05-22T15:34:05.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905488/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905488/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905488/answer","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905488/answer/previousversion/59121","Biography information for Dominic Raab","7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-16","Housing: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how much money from the public purse was spent on housing in (a) Coventry South constituency, (b) Coventry, (c) the West Midlands and (d) the UK in each year since 1998.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","144793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905489","Home Office","false","2018-05-24","<p>The issue of education provision for children seeking asylum is an important one and the Home Office makes every effort to ensure that families with children who claim asylum support have access to education at the earliest opportunity.</p><p>To enable access to education, internal checks are in place to identify applications involving children of school age for priority dispersal from initial accommodation facilities into permanent accommodation.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-05-24T16:19:26.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905489/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905489/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905489/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-16","Asylum: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what support his Department makes available to ensure that newly arrived asylum seekers placed in initial accommodation have immediate access to the education system.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","144794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905490","Home Office","false","2018-05-25","<p>The Government works closely with other EU Member States to enact the safe transfers of unaccompanied asylum seeking children under the family reunion provisions of the Dublin Regulation, where they have eligible family in the UK. We have liaison officers based in France, Greece and Italy to support the transfer of unaccompanied children to the UK under the Dublin Regulation and section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016.</p><p>The Sandhurst Treaty, signed between the UK and France in January 2018, included measures to strengthen our cooperation with France on the operation of the Dublin Regulation, including shorter timescales for decisions and transfers. Where an unaccompanied child makes an asylum application in France, we will provide a decision to take charge of their claim within 10 working days of the conclusion of engagement with the relevant UK authority. Where we accept responsibility for assessing their asylum claim, we will aim, in cooperation with France, to transfer the child to the UK within 15 working days.</p><p>The Government has also announced a £3.6M development fund, which will be used to identify projects that support genuine claims through the Dublin process and ensure that those with no prospect of transferring to the UK are informed of their options.</p><p>The UK also continues our deployments to the European Asylum Support Office (EASO) to support their work in providing operational support to frontline Member States dealing with large numbers of migrant arrivals across Europe</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-05-25T09:53:27.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905490/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905490/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905490/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-16","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps his Department is taking to improve the processes for identifying children with rights to family reunion in the UK throughout refugee camps in Europe.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","144795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905491","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-05-21","<p>The Government has not declined any requests for financial flexibilities to assist local authorities in competing essential fire safety work.</p><p>We have listened to what social sector landlords have been telling us about the cost of Aluminium Composite Material cladding systems and the decisions that they are making about how to fund it. The Prime Minister announced on 16 May that the Government will fully fund the removal and replacement of dangerous cladding on building owned by councils and housing associations, with costs estimated at £400 million. We will also continue to offer financial flexibilities for local authorities who need to undertake other essential fire safety work. We want to allocate this funding as soon as possible and we will announce more details shortly, including how we will encourage landlords to continue to pursue other parties for costs where they are responsible or at fault.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-05-21T15:30:30.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905491/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905491/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905491/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-16","Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many requests for financial assistance to undertake fire safety work from local councils and housing associations has his Department refused since the Grenfell Tower fire; and of each such request what the sum of money applied for was.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","144961"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905492","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-25","<p>In England, Defra helps beekeepers tackle the challenges facing the honey bee through the work of the National Bee Unit (NBU). NBU Bee Inspectors carry out inspections for pests and diseases and provide at hive advice at over 5,000 apiaries each year. Where key pests and diseases are found the inspectors take necessary statutory action for their control. Education of beekeepers and sharing best practice are essential for healthy colonies. To this end the NBU has an extensive programme of education and training events throughout the year. We also provide some funding for the Bee Farmers Apprenticeship Scheme which aims to encourage young people to become commercial beekeepers.</p><p> </p><p>Contingency plans are in place outlining the Government’s response to the threat from exotic pests such as the Asian hornet. The plans have been successfully used to tackle Asian hornet outbreaks in the Southwest.</p><p> </p><p>Under the National Pollinator Strategy, we are encouraging the public to support honey bees and other pollinators by planting flowering plants and trees to improve the forage available and expand upon existing shelter and nest sites.</p><p> </p><p>We are committed to strict regulation of pesticides to ensure that they do not harm honeybees and other pollinators. Based on the scientific evidence, we supported the recent European Commission decision to tighten the existing restrictions on neonicotinoid insecticides.</p><p> </p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley",,"2018-05-25T13:35:08.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905492/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905492/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905492/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-16","Bees: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to help tackle the challenges faced by honeybees in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","144796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905493","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-23","<p>Promotion of individual food brands is a matter for the food industry. However, it is very important that food marketed as ‘gluten free’ or ‘very low gluten’ is correctly labelled and complies with the relevant legislation. The Food Standards Agency and Local Authority Trading Standards Departments are responsible for ensuring compliance with the relevant regulations.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-05-23T16:43:00.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905493/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905493/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905493/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-16","Coeliac Disease: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Department is taking to increase the availability of gluten-free food to consumers.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","144797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905494","Department for Transport","false","2018-05-23","<p>The Department has taken steps to improve wifi on rail services by putting in place requirements for the provision of wifi in franchise agreements.</p><p> </p><p>The Midland main line route is largely served by East Midlands, Cross Country and Thameslink, Southern and Great Northern (TSGN) franchises. These franchisees are implementing the requirement to have wifi available to passengers.</p><p> </p><p>The availability of phone signal on the rail network is led by the Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport. Work is underway by Ofcom to survey the availability of mobile signal on the rail network. We expect the first publication to be later this year.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-05-23T10:06:37.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905494/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905494/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905494/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-05-16","Midland Main Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment his Department has made of the (a) availability and (b) efficiency of (i) wi-fi and (ii) telephone signals on the Midland main line route.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","144798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905495","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-21","<p>As my Rt Hon Friend the Foreign Secretary said in the House on 15 May, it is Russia's responsibility to ensure the safety of all fans travelling to the World Cup. We will continue to work to ensure British nationals travelling have the best support possible and will have consular staff based in every city that England will play in. A number of staff across government are working on preparations for the World Cup; not all are based in Russia. As the Foreign Secretary said in his appearance before the Foreign Affairs Committee on 21 March, a member of the Diplomatic Service responsible for fan safety was expelled. An experienced consular official in the British Embassy in Russia has taken over the fan safety responsibilities within Russia.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-05-21T15:19:13.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905495/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905495/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905495/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-16","Russia: Football","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the member of British diplomatic staff with prime responsibility for the safety of UK fans at the 2018 World Cup has been expelled from Russia; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","144962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905496","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-25","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) has been unable to provide all the information requested. Where this is the case, I have provided an explanation. In addition, where staff numbers are below five people, I have not specified the exact figure. In addition, as a matter of policy, we do not disclose exact figures where staff numbers are below five people.</p><p>(a) As of 31 March each year between 2013 and 2018, the following number of Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) UK-based staff have been posted to the British Embassy in Pristina:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><em>Year</em></td><td><em>Number of FCO UK-Based Staff</em></td></tr><tr><td>2013</td><td>6</td></tr><tr><td>2014</td><td>7</td></tr><tr><td>2015</td><td>5</td></tr><tr><td>2016</td><td>Fewer than 5</td></tr><tr><td>2017</td><td>Fewer than 5</td></tr><tr><td>2018</td><td>Fewer than 5</td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>These numbers include staff who were on interchange from other Whitehall departments for the duration of their posting on FCO terms and conditions of service.</p><p>The FCO does not hold centrally a breakdown of how many FCO UK-based staff were overseas between 2008 to 2012. We are only able to provide information on the total FCO UK-based headcount data. The FCO outlined these figures in a previous Parliamentary Question (142785):</p><p><a href="https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmhansrd/cm130226/text/130226w0002.htm" target="_blank">https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmhansrd/cm130226/text/130226w0002.htm</a></p><p>(b) The Government provided secondees to the United Nations Mission in Kosovo (UNMIK) between 1999 and 2008. However in the timeframe available, we cannot ascertain whether any such secondees remained in post after 2008. The FCO does not currently second staff to UNMIK.</p><p>(c) The FCO does not second staff to the NATO Kosovo Force (KFOR). Each year from 2009 to 2016, there were UK-based Ministry of Defence (MOD) civilian staff deployed to Kosovo as Deputy Director or Director to the NATO Advisory and Liaison Team (and its predecessor organisations). The FCO currently seconds external staff to the NATO Advisory and Liaison Team. The number each year is under five.</p><p>(d) The FCO supplied the following numbers of secondees to the EU Rule of Law Mission in Kosovo (EULEX) since 2011. Data on secondees prior to 2011 is not held centrally.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Year</strong></td><td><strong>Number of UK secondments to EULEX</strong></td></tr><tr><td>2018</td><td>8 (including secondees to the Specialist Chambers/Special Prosecutor's Office in the Hague)</td></tr><tr><td>2017</td><td>9 (including secondees to the Specialist Chambers/Special Prosecutor's Office in the Hague)</td></tr><tr><td>2016</td><td>9</td></tr><tr><td>2014</td><td>43</td></tr><tr><td>2013</td><td>37</td></tr><tr><td>2012</td><td>61</td></tr><tr><td>2011</td><td><p>30</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>(e) Staff have been seconded by the FCO to the EU Special Representative (EUSR) in Kosovo. The number each year was under five. Staff have previously been seconded by the UK to the Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) mission in Kosovo. However, from 2008 onwards, these secondees were not paid by the Government; they received living allowances from the OSCE. From 2009 to 2012, seven staff were seconded to the International Civilian Office.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-05-25T11:06:34.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905496/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905496/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905496/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Kosovo","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many staff from his Department or seconded from other Ministerial Departments have been assigned to roles in the (a) British Embassy, Pristina, (b) United Nations Mission in Kosovo, (c) NATO Kosovo Force, (d) European Union Rule of Law Mission in Kosovo and (e) other international organisations' missions in Kosovo in each year since 2008.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","144843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905497","Department for International Development","false","2018-05-23","<p>No DFID staff have been assigned to the British Embassy, United Nations Mission, NATO Kosovo Force, European Union Rule of Law Mission or any other international organisations since 2010. DFID does not hold such records prior to 2010.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-05-23T16:11:18.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905497/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905497/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905497/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-05-16","Department for International Development: Kosovo","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many staff from her Department have been assigned to roles in the (a) British Embassy, Pristina, (b) United Nations Mission in Kosovo, (c) NATO Kosovo Force, (d) European Union Rule of Law Mission in Kosovo and (e) other international organisations' missions in Kosovo in each year since 2008.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","144844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905498","Home Office","false","2018-05-24","<p>The Home Office has no centrally held record of any staff or UK police officers being posted to a role in the British Embassy in Pristina from 2008 to date. Since 2013, 4 police officers have been deployed to the European Union Rule of Law Mission in Kosovo. We have no centrally held records covering Home Office staff or police officers being deployed to other agencies relating to Kosovo or the period before 2013.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-05-24T16:05:41.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905498/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905498/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905498/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-16","Home Office and Police: Kosovo","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many (a) staff from his Department and (b) officers from UK police forces have been assigned to roles in the (i) British Embassy, Pristina, (ii) United Nations Mission in Kosovo, (iii) NATO Kosovo Force, (iv) European Union Rule of Law Mission in Kosovo, and (v) other international organisations' missions in Kosovo in each year since 2008.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","144845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905499","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-05-25","<p>It is not possible to provide a complete answer as the information is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p><p>In 2008 the UK Defence Attaché (DA) to Kosovo was based in Pristina but has been non-resident since 2009. Since 2009 there has been one officer deployed as Advisor to the Commander of Kosovo Security Force. In 2017 two officers were deployed to KFOR HQ as staff officers and a 29 person Intelligence, Surveillance and Reconnaissance (ISR) Task Force (one officer and 28 other ranks) deployed to support KFOR, with two staff officers and an ISR Task Force of 31 personnel similarly deployed in 2018. Each year from 2009 to 2016 there was one UK-based Ministry of Defence civilian deployed to Kosovo as a deputy director or director to the NATO Advisory and Liaison Team (and its predecessor organisations). All posts have been funded through the Conflict, Security and Stability Fund (CSSF) apart from the DA.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2018-05-25T13:16:03.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905499/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905499/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905499/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-05-16","Ministry of Defence: Kosovo","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) civilian staff from his Department, (b) military officers and (c) other ranks have been assigned to roles in the (i) British Embassy, Pristina, (ii) United Nations Mission in Kosovo, (iii) NATO Kosovo Force, (iv) European Union Rule of Law Mission in Kosovo and (v) other international organisations' missions in Kosovo in each year since 2008.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","144846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905500","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-05-21","<p>HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service (HMCTS) monitors the number of panel members required for Social Security and Child Support appeals. As a result, in 2017/18 and 2018/19 the Judicial Appointments Commission has been recruiting extra judicial office holders to the Social Security and Child Support Tribunal, where Personal Independent Payment appeals are heard, resulting in the following appointments: -</p><ul><li>250 fee paid judges (across the First-tier Tribunal)</li><li>16 salaried judges</li><li>125 disability qualified members</li><li>226 medical members</li></ul><p> </p><p>Panel members who sit on Social Security and Child Support appeal panels hear appeals on a range of benefits, one of which is Personal Independence Payment. Information is not held centrally on levels of turnover specific to that benefit.</p><p> </p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-05-21T16:51:01.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905500/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905500/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905500/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-05-16","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment she has made of trends in the level of turnover of the membership of personal independence payment appeal tribunals.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","144829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905501","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-25","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) has been unable to provide all the information requested. Where this is the case, we have provided an explanation.</p><p>(a) The UK's share of the budget for the United Nations Interim Administration Mission in Kosovo (UNMIK) is paid from the UK's Peacekeeping Budget. Our contribution to this is funded from the Government's Conflict Stability and Security Fund (CSSF). The UK's share of the UN Peacekeeping Budget is currently 5.8%. Our payments to the UN Peacekeeping Budget for the last seven financial years are as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Financial Year</strong></td><td><strong>Payment</strong></td></tr><tr><td>17/18</td><td>£1.4m</td></tr><tr><td>16/17</td><td>£1.2m</td></tr><tr><td>15/16</td><td>£1.4m</td></tr><tr><td>14/15</td><td>£1.6m</td></tr><tr><td>13/14</td><td>£1.6m</td></tr><tr><td>12/13</td><td>£2.2m</td></tr><tr><td>11/12</td><td>£1.8m</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Data prior to FY 2011/12 is not available on the FCO's current system. To search the archives would incur disproportionate costs.</p><p>(b) The UK's contribution to the European Union Rule of Law Mission in Kosovo (EULEX) comes from our overall contribution to the EU's Common Foreign and Security Policy (CFSP) budget, which is calculated on the basis of Member States' GDP. We do not make mission specific contributions. To give an indication of costs, we pay £34m per year to cover all EU CSDP Missions (Peacekeeping and non-Peacekeeping).</p><p>(c) The UK contributes to the NATO Kosovo Force through our overall contributions to NATO Operation Balkans, in accordance with the UK's NATO cost share in force at the time that the budget was set. Records accessible in the time available date back to 2009 and set out the UK's contribution to Operation Balkans:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><strong>Year</strong></td><td><strong>Payment (Euros)</strong></td><td><strong>UK's NATO cost share</strong></td></tr><tr><td>2009</td><td>3.086m</td><td>12.0542%</td></tr><tr><td>2010</td><td>2.910m</td><td>11.5478%</td></tr><tr><td>2012</td><td>2.803m</td><td>11.1677%</td></tr><tr><td>2013</td><td>2.801m</td><td>11.1677%</td></tr><tr><td>2014</td><td>2.588m</td><td>10.4790%</td></tr><tr><td>2015</td><td>2.494m</td><td>10.4790%</td></tr><tr><td>2016</td><td>2.039m</td><td>9.8485%</td></tr><tr><td>2017</td><td>2.245m</td><td>9.8485%</td></tr><tr><td>2018</td><td>2.384m</td><td>10.4581%</td></tr></tbody></table><p>(d) In 2018, the total funds allocated to the Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) Field Operations was €79.5m, of which €17.4m was allocated to its mission in Kosovo. The UK's share of this allocation was 11.09%.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-05-25T11:09:17.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905501/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905501/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905501/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-16","Kosovo: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the UK's financial contribution to the budgets of the (a) United Nations Interim Administration Mission in Kosovo, (b) European Union Rule of Law Mission in Kosovo, (c) NATO Kosovo Force and (d) other international organisations' missions in Kosovo has been in each year since 2008.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","144847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905502","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-22","<p>Children and young people with serious or critical illnesses such as cancer are able to apply for Disability Living Allowance (DLA) if they are aged under 16 (or Personal Independence Payment (PIP) if aged 16 and above).</p><p> </p><p>DLA and PIP are both tax free allowances designed to contribute to the extra costs incurred as a result of long-term health conditions and/or disabilities. Children and young people in receipt of DLA or PIP can receive up to £145.35 a week. Entitlement to DLA and PIP depends on the effects that severe disability has on a person’s life and not on a particular disability or diagnosis. This is because people living with the same illnesses or disabilities may not necessarily have the same care or mobility needs.</p><p> </p><p>Special considerations are made for children and adults who are terminally ill. Our arrangements recognise the particular difficulties faced by people who have only a short time to live. Claims are ‘fast-tracked’ and given immediate priority in the system and will be actioned as soon as they are received which is usually on the same day. The highest rate of the care component of DLA and enhanced rate of daily living component of PIP are awarded without a qualifying period. Legislation defines a person as terminally ill if ‘he suffers from a progressive disease and his death can reasonably be expected within six months’.</p><p>People over the age of 16 who are unable to work due to an illness or disability can claim Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) which has both a contributory strand accessible via a National Insurance contribution test and an income-related strand accessible via an income test. For cancer sufferers, a light touch evidence gathering process exists, to help determine eligibility. There is also a presumption that claimants receiving or recovering from cancer treatment will be placed in the Support Group which could entitle them to up to £110.75 per week, subject to suitable evidence from a healthcare professional such as a GP or oncologist.</p><p> </p><p>Carers may also be able to qualify for Carer’s Allowance, which is currently £64.60 a week if they meet the eligibility criteria.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-05-22T14:29:32.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905502/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905502/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905502/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-16","Social Security Benefits: Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent assessment she has made of whether the benefits system is providing adequate financial support for young cancer patients and their families.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","144819"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905503","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-21","<p>The latest official data available from the Office for National Statistics (ONS) estimates that 1.41 million 16 to 24 year olds were working part-time from January-December 2017. This represented 36.6% of 16-24 year olds in employment, down from 1.45 million young people working part time in January-December 2012 (39.9% of 16-24 year olds in employment).</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-05-21T13:51:04.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905503/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905503/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905503/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-16","Part-time Employment: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people between 16 and 24 years old were in part-time employment in (a) 2012 and (b) 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","144841"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905504","Department for International Trade","false","2018-05-23","<p>The UK Government has provided a coordinated, joined up package of support to those UK companies pursuing opportunities as part of the TF-X fighter aircraft programme. This includes Government to Government bilateral meetings and high level interventions, to support the ongoing diplomatic liaison between business and government (in the UK and Turkey) over the last three years.</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart",,"2018-05-23T13:02:01.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905504/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905504/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905504/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-05-16","Turkey: Military Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what diplomatic steps the Government has taken to support UK industry in its pursuit of Turkish TF-X fighter aircraft contracts.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","144848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905505","Home Office","false","2018-10-10","<p>No one who has contacted the Department’s Taskforce for Windrush has subsequently experienced immigration enforcement action as a result of coming forward. We are very clear that information to taskforce will not be passed for enforcement.</p><p>As at 17 May 2018, 7 individuals who have contacted the Windrush Taskforce, have also been identified as being wanted in connection to an on-going criminal investigation and have been referred to the Police. How the Police then decided to handle the matter is for them, and not something that the Taskforce are involved in, as it is not related to an immigration matter.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-10-10T15:59:42.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905505/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905505/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905505/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-16","Immigration: Windrush Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people who contacted his Department's Taskforce for Windrush subsequently experienced (a) immigrant enforcement and (b) police action.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","144786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905506","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-23","<p>The United Kingdom continues to support Taiwan’s meaningful participation in international organisations where statehood is not a prerequisite and where Taiwan can make a valuable contribution. The UK believes the World Health Assembly (WHA) meets these criteria.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has supported the Foreign and Commonwealth Office. We have worked with likeminded countries to lobby the World Health Organization at official level to issue an invitation to Taiwan to observe the WHA.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","144883","2018-05-23T15:14:34.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905506/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905506/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905506/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-16","World Health Assembly: Taiwan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether his Department plans to support Taiwan's participation in the World Health Assembly; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Martin Vickers","Cleethorpes","Martin Vickers","144882"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905507","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-23","<p>The United Kingdom continues to support Taiwan’s meaningful participation in international organisations where statehood is not a prerequisite and where Taiwan can make a valuable contribution. The UK believes the World Health Assembly (WHA) meets these criteria.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has supported the Foreign and Commonwealth Office. We have worked with likeminded countries to lobby the World Health Organization at official level to issue an invitation to Taiwan to observe the WHA.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","144882","2018-05-23T15:14:34.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905507/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905507/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905507/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-16","World Health Assembly: Taiwan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to encourage the World Health Organisation to facilitate Taiwan's attendance as an observer in the 2018 World Health Assembly.","false","Biography information for Martin Vickers","Cleethorpes","Martin Vickers","144883"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905508","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-05-21","<p>Our Industrial Strategy recognises the role of new markets like space launch in driving growth across the UK. The Government is delivering a major programme to enable companies to offer small satellite launch and sub-orbital spaceflight from UK spaceports</p><p> </p><p>We have considered 26 proposals for grant funding and expect to make an announcement on the results of this process shortly.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-05-21T13:56:27.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905508/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905508/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905508/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-16","Space Technology: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the timetable is for sites to be informed whether they have been successful in securing a grant towards development as a spaceport.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","144941"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905509","Prime Minister","false","2018-05-25","<p><em> </em>I refer the hon. Member to the press release issued on 15 May 2018 following my meeting with President Erdogan and which is available on the <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">gov.uk</a> website:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/pm-statement-with-president-erdogan" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/pm-statement-with-president-erdogan</a></p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May","146322","2018-05-25T12:08:21.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905509/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905509/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905509/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2018-05-16","Gaza: Israel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, what discussions she has had with President Erdogan of Turkey on the violence at the Gaza Border of 14 May 2018.","false","Biography information for Rosie Duffield","Canterbury","Rosie Duffield","144974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905510","Department for International Development","false","2018-05-22","<p>The UK government is well aware of the barriers faced by global and regional civil society networks pressing for a human rights-based response to HIV. That is why the UK government played a leadership role with other founding donors in setting up the Robert Carr Civil Society Networks Fund. So far the UK has committed £9 million. We will make our decision on future investments to the Fund later this year.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-05-22T16:55:05.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905510/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905510/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/905510/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-05-16","Developing Countries: HIV Infection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to ensure the (a) adequacy and (b) reliability of funding provided by her Department to (i) regional and (ii) global civil society network programmes to respond to the HIV epidemic.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","144931"
